FT  12 FEB 93 / Technology: A new resin takes the floor - Worth Watching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Formaldehyde is widely used in the production of vinyl kitchen floors and
other flooring and roofing materials - but it's best known as a poison.
Most attempts to find a substitute have failed on grounds of physical
performance. But a company in Philadelphia claims to have developed an
alternative that matches the performance of formaldehyde binders and resins.
Rohm and Haas say the tensile strength of its water-based acrylic resin
permits lower fibreglass weights and therefore cuts costs. Rohm and Haas:
US, 215 592 3000; UK, 081 686 8844.
